    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, this is the construction: a groupoid X gives a vector space [X] whose basis consists of isomorphism classes of objects in X, and a span from X to Y gives a linear operator from [X] to [Y].   I explain this in <a href=\"https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/week256.html\">week256</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So, let's finally figure out how a span of groupoids</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>                   S\n                  / \\\n                 /   \\\n                /     \\\n               v       v\n              X         Y\n</code></pre></div>\n\n<p>gives a linear operator</p>\n<p>[S]: [X] → [Y]</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 272339944,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645141008
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I should have pointed you to this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/groupoidification/\">Groupoidification</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>which has the whole Tale of Groupoidification in one place, and also two papers that go into more detail: \"Groupoidification made easy\" and \"Higher-dimensional algebra VII: groupoidification.\"</p>",
        "id": 272340196,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1645141195
    }
